    {
      "content": "Overview",
      "pos": [
        570,
        578
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Microsoft Azure Content Delivery Network (CDN) offers developers a global solution for delivering high-bandwidth content that is hosted in Azure.",
      "pos": [
        580,
        729
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The CDN caches publicly available objects loaded from Azure blob storage or an application folder at strategically placed locations to provide maximum bandwidth for delivering content to users.",
      "pos": [
        730,
        923
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is typically used for delivering static content such as images, style sheets, documents, files, client-side scripts, and HTML pages.",
      "pos": [
        924,
        1059
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The major advantages of using the CDN are lower latency and faster delivery of content to users irrespective of their geographical location in relation to the datacenter where the application is hosted, and a reduction in the load on the application itself because it is relieved of the processing required to access and deliver the content.",
      "pos": [
        1061,
        1402
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This reduction in load can help to increase the performance and scalability of the application, as well as minimizing hosting cost by reducing the processing resources required to achieve a specific level of performance and availability.",
      "pos": [
        1403,
        1640
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You may be able to use other content delivery network systems that are not implemented by Azure in your applications if the Azure CDN does not meet your needs.",
      "pos": [
        1642,
        1801
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Alternatively, you may be able to use the Azure CDN for applications hosted with other providers by exposing the static content in Azure storage or in Azure compute instances.",
      "pos": [
        1802,
        1977
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "How and why the CDN is used",
      "pos": [
        2022,
        2049
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Typical uses for the CDN include:",
      "pos": [
        2051,
        2084
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Delivering static resources for client applications, often from a website.",
      "pos": [
        2090,
        2164
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These can be images, style sheets, documents, files, client-side scripts, HTML pages, HTML fragments, or any other content that the server does not need to modify for each request.",
      "pos": [
        2165,
        2345
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The application can create items at runtime and make them available to the CDN (for example, by creating a list of current news headlines), but it does not do so for each request.",
      "pos": [
        2346,
        2525
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Delivering public static and shared content to devices such as mobile phones and tablet computers where the application itself is a web service that offers an API to clients.",
      "pos": [
        2529,
        2703
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition to other content that the server does not need to modify for each request, the CDN can deliver static datasets for the client to use - perhaps to generate the client UI.",
      "pos": [
        2704,
        2885
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, it could be used to deliver JSON or XML documents.",
      "pos": [
        2886,
        2949
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Serving entire websites that consist of only public static content to clients, without requiring any dedicated compute resources.",
      "pos": [
        2953,
        3082
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Streaming video files to the client on demand.",
      "pos": [
        3086,
        3132
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Video benefits from the low latency and reliable connectivity available from the globally located datacenters that offer CDN connections.",
      "pos": [
        3133,
        3270
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Generally improving the experience for users, especially those located far from the applicationâ€™s datacenter location who would otherwise suffer higher latency.",
      "pos": [
        3274,
        3434
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A large proportion of the total size of the content in a web application is often static, and using the CDN can help to maintain performance and overall user experience while eliminating the requirement to deploy the application to multiple data centers.",
      "pos": [
        3435,
        3689
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Coping with the growing load on applications that service mobile and fixed devices that are part of the Internet of Things (IoT).",
      "pos": [
        3693,
        3822
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The huge numbers of such devices and appliances could easily overwhelm the application if it was required to process broadcast messages and manage firmware update distribution directly.",
      "pos": [
        3823,
        4008
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Coping with peaks and surges in demand without requiring the application to scale, avoiding the consequent increase running costs.",
      "pos": [
        4012,
        4142
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, when an update is released to an operating system, for a hardware device such as a specific model of router, or for a consumer device such as a smart TV, there will be a huge peak in demand as it is downloaded by millions of users and devices over a short period.",
      "pos": [
        4143,
        4419
      ]
    },
