    {
      "content": "Challenges",
      "pos": [
        5350,
        5360
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are several challenges to take into account when planning to use the CDN:",
      "pos": [
        5364,
        5443
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        5449,
        5702
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Deployment<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> You must decide where to load content for the CDN from (the origin from which the CDN will fetch the content), and whether you need to deploy the content in more than one storage system (such as on the CDN and in an alternative location)."
    },
    {
      "content": "Your application deployment mechanism must take into account deploying static content and resources as well as deploying the application files such as ASPX pages.",
      "pos": [
        5706,
        5868
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, it may require a separate step to load content into Azure blob storage.",
      "pos": [
        5869,
        5953
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Versioning and cache-control<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> You must consider how you will update static content and deploy new versions.",
      "pos": [
        5957,
        6067
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The CDN does not currently provide a mechanism for flushing content so that new versions are available.",
      "pos": [
        6068,
        6171
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is a similar challenge to managing client side caching, such as in a web browser.",
      "pos": [
        6172,
        6258
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6262,
        6405
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Testing<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> It can be difficult to perform local testing of your CDN settings when developing and testing an application locally or in staging."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6409,
        6562
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>SEO<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Content such as images and documents are served from a different domain when you use they CDN, which will have an effect on SEO for this content."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6566,
        6681
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Security<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Many CDN services such as Azure CDN do not currently offer any type of access control for the content."
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Resiliency<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> CDN is a potential single point of failure for an application.",
      "pos": [
        6685,
        6762
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It has a lower availability SLA than blob storage (which can be used to deliver content directly) so you may need to consider implementing a fallback mechanism for critical content.",
      "pos": [
        6763,
        6944
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Clients may be connecting from an environment that does not allow access to resources on the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        6948,
        7045
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This could be a security-constrained environment that limits access to only a set of known sources, or one that prevents loading of resources from anything other than the page origin.",
      "pos": [
        7046,
        7229
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Therefore, a fallback implementation will be required.",
      "pos": [
        7230,
        7284
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You should implement a mechanism to monitor your content availability through the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        7288,
        7374
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Scenarios where CDN may be less useful include:",
      "pos": [
        7376,
        7423
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the content has a low hit rate and so may be accessed few times, or just once, during the time-to-live validity period.",
      "pos": [
        7429,
        7553
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The first time an item is downloaded you incur two transaction charges (from the origin to the CDN, and then from the CDN to the customer).",
      "pos": [
        7554,
        7693
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the data is private, such as for large enterprises or supply chain ecosystems.",
      "pos": [
        7697,
        7780
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "General guidelines and good practices",
      "pos": [
        7786,
        7823
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using the CDN is a good way to minimize the load on your application, and maximize availability and performance.",
      "pos": [
        7825,
        7937
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You should consider this for all of the appropriate content and resources you application uses.",
      "pos": [
        7938,
        8033
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Consider the following points when designing your strategy to use the CDN:",
      "pos": [
        8034,
        8108
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Origin<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Deploying content through the CDN simply requires you to specify an HTTP (port 80) endpoint that the CDN service will use to access and cache the content.",
      "pos": [
        8114,
        8279
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "+ The endpoint can specify an Azure blob storage container that holds the static content you want to deliver through the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        8280,
        8405
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The container must be marked as public.",
      "pos": [
        8406,
        8445
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Only blobs in a public container that have public read access will be available through the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        8446,
        8542
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The endpoint can specify a folder named <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>cdn<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> in the root of one of applicationâ€™s compute layers (such as a web role or a virtual machine).",
      "pos": [
        8546,
        8687
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The results from requests for resources, including dynamic resources such as ASPX pages, will be cached on the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        8688,
        8803
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The minimum cacheability period is 300 seconds.",
      "pos": [
        8804,
        8851
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Any shorter period will prevent the content from being deployed to the CDN (see the section \"<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a href=\"#cachecontrol\" xmlns:dt=\"uuid:C2F41010-65B3-11d1-A29F-00AA00C14882\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xmlns:MSHelp=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/mshelp\"&gt;</ph>Cache control<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>\" for more information).",
      "pos": [
        8852,
        9154
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are using Azure Web Sites, the endpoint is set to the root folder of the site by selecting the site when creating the CDN instance.",
      "pos": [
        9158,
        9296
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "All of the content for the site will be available through the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        9297,
        9363
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In most cases, pointing your CDN endpoint at a folder within one of the compute layers of your application will offer more flexibility and control.",
      "pos": [
        9367,
        9514
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For instance, it makes it easier to manage current and future routing requirements, and dynamically generate static content such as image thumbnails.",
      "pos": [
        9515,
        9664
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use query strings to differentiate objects in the cache when content is delivered from dynamic sources such as ASPX pages.",
      "pos": [
        9668,
        9798
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, this behavior can be disabled by a setting in the management portal when you specify the CDN endpoint.",
      "pos": [
        9799,
        9910
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When delivering content from blob storage, query strings are treated as string literals so two items that have the same name but different query strings will be stored as separate items on the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        9911,
        10108
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can utilize URL rewriting for resources such as scripts and other content to avoid moving your files to the CDN origin folder.",
      "pos": [
        10112,
        10242
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When using Azure storage blobs to hold content for the CDN, the URL of the resources in blobs is case sensitive for the container and blob name.",
      "pos": [
        10246,
        10390
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When using Azure Web Sites, you specify the path to the CDN instance in the links to resources.",
      "pos": [
        10394,
        10489
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, the following specifies an image file in the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Images<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> folder of the site that will be delivered through the CDN:",
      "pos": [
        10490,
        10617
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Deployment<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Static content may need to be provisioned and deployed independently from the application if you do not include it in the application deployment package or process.",
      "pos": [
        10708,
        10887
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Consider how this will affect the versioning approach you use to manage both the application components and the static resource content.",
      "pos": [
        10888,
        11024
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Consider how bundling (combining several files into one file) and minification (removing unnecessary characters such as white space, new line characters, comments, and other characters) for script and CSS files will be handled.",
      "pos": [
        11028,
        11255
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These commonly used techniques can reduce load times for clients, and are compatible with delivering content through the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        11256,
        11381
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Bundling and Minification<ept id=\"p1\">](http://www.asp.net/mvc/tutorials/mvc-4/bundling-and-minification)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        11382,
        11502
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you need to deploy the content to an additional location, this will be an extra step in the deployment process.",
      "pos": [
        11506,
        11620
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the application updates the content for the CDN, perhaps at regular intervals or in response to an event, it must store the updated content in any additional locations as well as the endpoint for the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        11621,
        11828
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You cannot set up a CDN endpoint for an application deployed in Azure staging, or in the local Azure emulator in Visual Studio.",
      "pos": [
        11832,
        11959
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This will affect unit testing, functional testing, and final pre-deployment testing.",
      "pos": [
        11960,
        12044
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You must allow for this by implementing an alternative mechanism.",
      "pos": [
        12045,
        12110
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, you could pre-deploy the content to the CDN using a temporary custom application or utility, and perform testing during the period it is cached.",
      "pos": [
        12111,
        12268
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Alternatively, use compile directives or global constants to control where the application loads the resources from.",
      "pos": [
        12269,
        12385
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, when running in debug mode it could load resources such as client-side script bundles and other content from a local folder, and use the CDN when running in release mode.",
      "pos": [
        12386,
        12569
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The CDN does not support any native compression capabilities.",
      "pos": [
        12573,
        12634
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, it will deliver content that is already compressed, such as zip and gzip files.",
      "pos": [
        12635,
        12723
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When using an application folder as the CDN endpoint, the server may compress some content by default in the same way as when delivering it directly to a web browser or other type of client.",
      "pos": [
        12724,
        12914
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This relies on the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Accept-Encoding<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> value sent from the client.",
      "pos": [
        12915,
        12981
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In Azure the default is to automatically compress content when CPU utilization is below 50%.",
      "pos": [
        12982,
        13074
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Changing the settings and may require use of a startup task to turn on compression of dynamic output in IIS if you are using Cloud Services to host the application.",
      "pos": [
        13075,
        13239
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Enabling gzip compression with Azure CDN through a Web Role<ept id=\"p1\">](http://blogs.msdn.com/b/avkashchauhan/archive/2012/03/05/enableing-gzip-compression-with-windows-azure-cdn-through-web-role.aspx)</ept> for more information.",
      "pos": [
        13240,
        13457
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Routing and versioning<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> You may need to use different CDN instances; for example, when you deploy a new version of the application you may want to use a different CDN.",
      "pos": [
        13461,
        13631
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you use Azure blob storage as the content origin, you can simply create a separate storage account or a separate container and point the CDN endpoint to it.",
      "pos": [
        13632,
        13791
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you use the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>cdn<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> root folder within the application as the CDN endpoint you can use URL rewriting techniques to direct requests to a different folder.",
      "pos": [
        13792,
        13948
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Do not use the query string to denote different versions of the application in links to resources on the CDN because, when drawing content from Azure blob storage, the query string is part of the resource name (the blob name).",
      "pos": [
        13952,
        14178
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It can also affect how the client caches the resources.",
      "pos": [
        14179,
        14234
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Deploying new versions of static content when you update an application can be a challenge if the previous resources are cached on the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        14238,
        14377
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see the section \"<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a href=\"#cachecontrol\" xmlns:dt=\"uuid:C2F41010-65B3-11d1-A29F-00AA00C14882\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xmlns:MSHelp=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/mshelp\"&gt;</ph>Cache control<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>\".",
      "pos": [
        14378,
        14604
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"cachecontrol\" href=\"#\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;span /&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph><bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Cache control<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>+ Consider how you want to manage caching, and at what layers of the application.",
      "pos": [
        14606,
        14791
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, when using a folder as the CDN origin you can specify the cacheability of pages that generate the content, and the content expiry for all the resources in a specific folder.",
      "pos": [
        14792,
        14978
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also specify cache properties for the CDN, and for the client using standard HTTP headers.",
      "pos": [
        14979,
        15077
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Although you should already be managing caching on the server and client, using the CDN will help to make you more aware of how your content is cached, and where.",
      "pos": [
        15078,
        15240
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To prevent objects from being available on the CDN you can delete them from the origin (blob container or application <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>cdn<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> root folder), remove or delete the CDN endpoint, orâ€”in the case of blob storageâ€”make the container or blob private.",
      "pos": [
        15244,
        15485
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, items will be removed from the CDN only when their time-to-live (TTL) expires.",
      "pos": [
        15486,
        15573
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If no cache expiry period is specified (such as when content is loaded from blob storage), it will be cached on the CDN for up to 72 hours.",
      "pos": [
        15577,
        15716
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In a web application, you can set the caching and expiry for all content by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>clientCache<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> element in the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>system.webServer/staticContent<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> section of a web.config file.",
      "pos": [
        15720,
        15901
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can place a web.config file in any folder so that it affects the files in that folder and the files in all subfolders.",
      "pos": [
        15902,
        16024
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you use a dynamic technique such as ASP.NET to create the content for the CDN, ensure that you specify the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Cache.SetExpires<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> property on each page.",
      "pos": [
        16028,
        16181
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The CDN will not cache the output from pages that use the default cacheability setting of public.",
      "pos": [
        16182,
        16279
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Set the cache expiry period to a suitable value to ensure that the content is not discarded and reloaded from the application at very short intervals.",
      "pos": [
        16281,
        16431
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Security<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> The CDN can deliver content over HTTPS (SSL) using the certificate provided by the CDN, but it will also be available over HTTP as well.",
      "pos": [
        16437,
        16586
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You cannot block HTTP access to items in the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        16587,
        16636
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You may need to use HTTPS to request static content that is displayed in pages loaded through HTTPS (such as a shopping cart) to avoid browser warnings about mixed content.",
      "pos": [
        16637,
        16809
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Many CDN services, such as the Azure CDN, do not presently offer any facilities for access control to secure access to the content.",
      "pos": [
        16813,
        16944
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You cannot use Shared Access Signatures (SAS) with the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        16945,
        17004
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you deliver client-side scripts using the CDN, you may encounter issues if these scripts use an <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>XMLHttpRequest<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> call to make HTTP requests for other resources such as data, images, or fonts in a different domain.",
      "pos": [
        17008,
        17226
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Many web browsers prevent cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) unless the web server is configured to set the appropriate response headers.",
      "pos": [
        17227,
        17366
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information about CORS, see the section \"Threat mitigation\" in the guide <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;span class=\"highlight\" xmlns:dt=\"uuid:C2F41010-65B3-11d1-A29F-00AA00C14882\" xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" xmlns:MSHelp=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/mshelp\"&gt;</ph>API security considerations<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/span&gt;</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        17367,
        17652
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can configure the CDN to support CORS:+ If the origin from which you are delivering content is Azure blob storage, you can add a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CorsRule<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to the service properties.",
      "pos": [
        17653,
        17825
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The rule can specify the allowed origins for CORS requests, the allowed methods such as GET, and the maximum age in seconds for the rule (the period within which the client must request the linked resources after loading the original content).",
      "pos": [
        17826,
        18069
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) Support for the Azure Storage Services<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn535601.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        18070,
        18229
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the origin from which you are delivering content is a folder within the application, such as the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>cdn<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> root folder, you can configure outbound rules in the application configuration file to set an <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Access-Control-Allow-Origin<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> header on all responses.",
      "pos": [
        18233,
        18491
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information about using rewrite rules, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>URL Rewrite Module<ept id=\"p1\">](http://www.iis.net/learn/extensions/url-rewrite-module)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        18492,
        18621
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that this technique is not possible when using Azure Web Sites.",
      "pos": [
        18622,
        18690
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Custom domains<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>+ Most CDNs, including the Azure CDN, allow you to specify a custom domain name and use it to access resources through the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        18694,
        18839
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can also set up a custom subdomain name using a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CNAME<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> record in your DNS.",
      "pos": [
        18840,
        18921
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using this approach can provide an additional layer of abstraction and control.",
      "pos": [
        18922,
        19001
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        19005,
        19202
      ],
      "content": "If you use a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CNAME<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, you cannot (at the time this guide was written) also use SSL because the CDN uses its own single SSL certificate, and this will not match your custom domain/subdomain names."
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CDN fallback<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> You should consider how your application will cope with a failure or temporary unavailability of the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        19206,
        19328
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Client applications may be able to use copies of the resources that were cached locally (on the client) during previous requests, or they can use code that detects failures and instead requests resources from the origin (the application folder or Azure blob container that holds the resources) if the CDN is unavailable.",
      "pos": [
        19329,
        19649
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        19653,
        19795
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>SEO<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> If SEO is an important consideration in your application, make sure you:+ Include a <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Rel<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> canonical header in each page or resource."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        19799,
        19873
      ],
      "content": "Use a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>CNAME<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> subdomain record and access the resources using this name."
    },
    {
      "content": "Consider the impact of the fact that the IP address of the CDN may be a country or region that differs from that of the application itself.",
      "pos": [
        19877,
        20016
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When using Azure blob storage as the origin, maintain the same file structure for resources on the CDN as in the application folders.",
      "pos": [
        20020,
        20153
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        20158,
        20310
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Monitoring &amp; Logging<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Include the CDN as part of your application monitoring strategy to detect and measure failures or extended latency occurrences."
    },
    {
      "content": "Enable logging for the CDN and include it as part of your daily operations.",
      "pos": [
        20314,
        20389
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Cost implication<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> You are charged for both outbound data transfers from the CDN and for storage transactions when the CDN loads data from your application.",
      "pos": [
        20393,
        20551
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You should set realistic cache expiry periods for content to ensure freshness, but not so short as to cause repeated reloading of content from the application or blob storage to the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        20552,
        20738
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, very long expiry periods make it more difficult to remove items from the CDN because you must wait for them to expire.",
      "pos": [
        20739,
        20866
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Items that are rarely downloaded will incur the two transaction charges without providing any significant reduction in server load.",
      "pos": [
        20870,
        21001
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Example code",
      "pos": [
        21010,
        21022
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This section contains some examples of code and techniques for working with the CDN.",
      "pos": [
        21023,
